 deathly presence. The book focuses on the poetic interpretations of the Canadian soldier. He emerges as a contentious poetic subject, a figure of battle romance, and an emblem of modernist fragmentation and fractiousness. Centring the work of five exemplary Canadian war poets (Helena Coleman, John McCrae, Robert Service, Frank Prewett, and W.W.E. Ross), the book reveals their latent faith in collective action as well as conflicting recognition of modernist subjectivities. Battle Lines identifies the Great War as a long-overlooked period of poetic ferment, experimentation, reluctance, and challenge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aWar in literature. 0aWar poetry, CanadianxHistory and criticism. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918vPoetry. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aHistory: Military History. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 4aPoetry. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh  aCanada and WWI.  aCanadian First World War poetry.  aCanadian literary history.  aCanadian modernism.  aCanadian poetry WWI.  aFrank Prewett.  aGreat War poetry.  aIn Flanders Fields.  aRobert Service.  aRupert Brooke.  aWWI poetry.  apatriotic poetry.  asoldier poetry.  awar poetry.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112320440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771123204423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771123204/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles